# Testing Guidelines for Anno

## Test Organization

### Test Tiers
| Tier | Profile | Timeout | Use Case |
|------|---------|---------|----------|
| Quick | `--profile quick` | 10s | Fast iteration, CI PR checks |
| Default | `--profile default` | 30s | Normal development |
| ML | `--profile ml` | 180s | Tests with model loading |
| Property | `--profile property` | 120s | Proptest/fuzz testing |
| CI | `--profile ci` | 60s | Full CI pipeline |

### Running Tests
```bash
# Fast development cycle
cargo nextest run --profile quick --lib --features "eval"

# Full suite before commit
cargo nextest run --profile ci --workspace --features "eval-advanced discourse"

# ML backend tests only
cargo nextest run --profile ml --features "onnx candle" -E 'test(/gliner/) or test(/candle/)'

# Property tests with more cases
PROPTEST_CASES=1000 cargo nextest run --profile property -E 'test(/property/)'
```

## Test Patterns

### Unit Tests
```rust
#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;
    
    #[test]
    fn test_basic_functionality() {
        // Fast, isolated, no external dependencies
    }
}
```

### Property Tests
```rust
use proptest::prelude::*;

// Reduced config for slow backends
fn slow_config() -> ProptestConfig {
    ProptestConfig {
        cases: 10,
        ..ProptestConfig::default()
    }
}

proptest! {
    #![proptest_config(slow_config())]
    
    #[test]
    fn invariant_holds(text in arb_text()) {
        // Property that should hold for all inputs
    }
}
```

### CLI Integration Tests
```rust
/// Helper to get CLI command using pre-built binary
fn anno_cmd() -> Command {
    if let Ok(bin_path) = std::env::var("ANNO_BIN") {
        return Command::new(bin_path);
    }
    
    let manifest_dir = std::path::Path::new(env!("CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR"));
    let workspace_root = manifest_dir.parent().unwrap();
    
    // Try release binary first (fastest)
    let release_bin = workspace_root.join("target/release/anno");
    if release_bin.exists() {
        return Command::new(release_bin);
    }
    
    // Fall back to debug binary
    let debug_bin = workspace_root.join("target/debug/anno");
    if debug_bin.exists() {
        return Command::new(debug_bin);
    }
    
    // Last resort: cargo run (slow)
    let mut cmd = Command::new("cargo");
    cmd.args(["run", "-p", "anno", "--bin", "anno", "--features", "cli eval", "--"]);
    cmd
}
```

## Feature-Gated Tests

```rust
// Only run when feature is enabled
#[test]
#[cfg(feature = "onnx")]
fn test_onnx_backend() { ... }

// Skip if model unavailable (graceful degradation)
#[test]
fn test_with_optional_model() {
    let model = match load_model() {
        Ok(m) => m,
        Err(_) => {
            eprintln!("Skipping: model not available");
            return;
        }
    };
    // ... test with model
}

// For NuNER/GLiNER ONNX smoke:
// - gate with `#[cfg(feature = "onnx")]`
// - skip unless `NUNER_ONNX_MODEL` env var is set
```

## Test Data

### Fixture Files
- Place in `testdata/` or `tests/fixtures/`
- Use `include_str!()` for embedded test data
- Prefer generated data over large fixture files
- ONNX smoke fixtures can live in `tests/data/` (e.g., `tests/data/ner/coarse_smoke.jsonl`) and should stay tiny and versioned

### Multilingual Test Data
Every test file should include diverse examples:
```rust
let test_texts = [
    "Barack Obama was born in Hawaii.",           // English
    "習近平是中國國家主席。",                        // Chinese
    "Angela Merkel war Bundeskanzlerin.",         // German
    "المملكة العربية السعودية",                    // Arabic
    "東京オリンピック2020",                         // Japanese
];
```

### Zero-shot / Label Pack Tests
- When adding new NER schemas or label packs, add unit tests that:
  - verify `with_label_pack` swaps defaults
  - ensure `map_label_to_entity_type` covers new labels
- Keep span decoding tests for fine/CNER labels and overlap resolution

## Assertion Patterns

### Entity Validation
```rust
fn assert_valid_entity(entity: &Entity, text: &str) {
    let char_count = text.chars().count();
    assert!(entity.start <= entity.end, "Invalid span: start > end");
    assert!(entity.end <= char_count, "Span exceeds text length");
    assert!(entity.confidence >= 0.0 && entity.confidence <= 1.0);
    assert!(!entity.text.is_empty(), "Empty entity text");
}
```

### Backend Invariants
```rust
// All backends should satisfy these
fn test_backend_invariants<B: Model>(backend: &B, text: &str) {
    let entities = backend.extract_entities(text, None).unwrap();
    
    for entity in &entities {
        // Valid spans
        assert!(entity.start <= entity.end);
        
        // Valid confidence
        assert!(entity.confidence >= 0.0);
        assert!(entity.confidence <= 1.0);
        
        // Non-empty text
        assert!(!entity.text.trim().is_empty());
    }
    
    // Determinism (same input → same output)
    let entities2 = backend.extract_entities(text, None).unwrap();
    assert_eq!(entities.len(), entities2.len());
}
```

## CI Configuration

### nextest.toml Profiles

Located at `.config/nextest.toml`:

```toml
[profile.quick]
retries = 0
slow-timeout = { period = "10s", terminate-after = 1 }
# Excludes: property tests, CLI integration, slow ML tests
# Use `binary(name)` for test binaries, `test(/regex/)` for test names
default-filter = "not test(/property/) and not binary(cli_context_output) and not binary(compare_command) and not binary(e2e_cli_workflows) and not test(/stacked.*proptest/) and not test(/eval.*harness/) and not test(/test_harness_synthetic/) and not test(/test_agreement_bonus/) and not test(/backend_availability_matrix/) and not test(/property_backends/) and not binary(task_evaluator_comprehensive) and not test(/test_layer_error_handling/) and not test(/randomized_matrix/)"

[profile.ml]
retries = 1
slow-timeout = { period = "180s", terminate-after = 3 }
test-threads = 2  # Limit parallelism for GPU/model tests

[profile.ci]
retries = 2
slow-timeout = { period = "60s", terminate-after = 2 }
fail-fast = true
```

### Feature Flag Combinations

```bash
# Core evaluation
cargo nextest run --profile quick -p anno --features "eval"

# Full eval with discourse analysis
cargo nextest run --profile quick --workspace --features "eval-full discourse"

# With ONNX backends (requires ONNX models)
cargo nextest run --profile ml -p anno --features "eval-full onnx"

# With Candle ML (pure Rust, no ONNX)
cargo nextest run --profile ml -p anno --features "eval-full candle"

# Everything except CUDA/Metal (platform-specific)
cargo nextest run --profile ml --workspace --features "eval-full discourse onnx candle"
```

### Pre-commit Checklist
1. Build release binary: `cargo build --release -p anno --bin anno --features "cli eval"`
2. Run quick tests: `cargo nextest run --profile quick`
3. Run lints: `cargo clippy --workspace --all-features`
4. Format: `cargo fmt --check`

## Debugging Failing Tests

```bash
# Run single test with output
cargo nextest run --no-capture test_name

# Run with backtrace
RUST_BACKTRACE=1 cargo nextest run test_name

# Run with debug logging
RUST_LOG=debug cargo nextest run test_name

# Profile slow tests
cargo nextest run --profile default --status-level all 2>&1 | grep SLOW
```

## CRITICAL: No Output Truncation

**NEVER pipe test output through `head`, `tail`, or `grep` to hide results.**

```bash
# BAD - hides important information
cargo nextest run 2>&1 | tail -20
cargo test 2>&1 | head -50
cargo check 2>&1 | grep error

# GOOD - see all output
cargo nextest run
cargo test
cargo check
```

Rationale:
- Truncating output hides important context about failures
- Errors may appear in the middle of output, not just at the end
- More context is always better for debugging
- Your AI assistant's context window can handle the full output
